  <div slot="content">
    <h1>Variables and Data Types</h1>
    
    <p>Variables are like containers that store data. In Python, you can create a variable by simply assigning a value to it.</p>
    
    <h2>Creating Variables</h2>
    
    <p>To create a variable, use the assignment operator <code>=</code>:</p>
    
    <pre><code>name = "Alice"
age = 25</code></pre>
    
    <h2>Data Types</h2>
    
    <p>Python has several basic data types:</p>
    
    <ul>
      <li><strong>String (str)</strong>: Text data, enclosed in quotes</li>
      <li><strong>Integer (int)</strong>: Whole numbers</li>
      <li><strong>Float</strong>: Decimal numbers</li>
      <li><strong>Boolean (bool)</strong>: True or False values</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Using Variables</h2>
    
    <p>Once you create a variable, you can use it in your code. You can also print variables using the <code>print()</code> function.</p>
    
    <h2>F-strings</h2>
    
    <p>F-strings are a convenient way to include variables in text. Put an <code>f</code> before the quotes and use <code>{`{variable_name}`}</code> inside:</p>
    
    <pre><code>name = "Alice"
print(f"Hello, {`{name}`}!")</code></pre>
    
    <h2>Try it yourself</h2>
    
    <p>Experiment with the code on the right. Try:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Changing the values of the variables</li>
      <li>Creating new variables</li>
      <li>Using different data types</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div slot="playground">
    <TutorialPlayground 
      code={`# Creating variables
